      "npc_notes": "ASCOMOID\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 3\nMOVE: 12\"\nHIT DICE: 6+6\n% IN LAIR: 40%\nTREASURE TYPE: Incidental\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1 point per 1' cloud diameter\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Spore jet, rolling attack\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Special weapon and magic resistances\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Special\nINTELLIGENCE: Unratable\nALIGNMENT: Neutral (evil)\nSIZE: L (5'-10' diameter)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: VII/775 + 8/hp\n\nAscomoids are giant puffball-like fungi covered in thick, leathery skin. They move by rolling. Their speed builds gradually: 3\" the first round, 6\" the next, then 9\", and finally 12\", and they can maintain that speed for hours.\n\nTheir surfaces are dotted with pocks that serve as sensory organs and also emit spores. They attack by rolling into or over opponents. Small and medium-sized creatures struck in this way are knocked down and must spend the following round rising, or remain prone.\n\nThe ascomoid also attacks with spore jets, especially against large opponents or any foe that has already injured it. A jet is roughly 1 foot in diameter and extends up to 30 feet. On impact it expands into a cloud 5-20 feet in diameter. Creatures in the cloud must save vs. poison or die from internal infection in 1-4 rounds. Even those who save are blinded and choking so badly that they require 1-4 rounds to recover enough to rejoin combat. Until then they are nearly helpless: attacks against them are at +4, and they lose shield and Dexterity bonuses.\n\nWeapon effects vary sharply. Piercing weapons such as long spears inflict double damage. Short stabbing weapons inflict damage only as though used against a small creature. Blunt weapons do not harm the ascomoid at all. Slashing and cutting weapons inflict only 1 point of damage. Magical attacks such as magic missile, fireball, and lightning bolt are saved against at +4, and only half damage is taken. Cold attacks work normally. Mind-affecting spells are useless unless they specifically affect plants.",
