      "npc_notes": "BARKBURR\n\nFREQUENCY: Rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-5\nARMOR CLASS: 0 (carapace) / 8 (underside)\nMOVE: ½\" on ground; leap to 20' from tree\nHIT DICE: 2-6\n% IN LAIR: 100%\nTREASURE TYPE: See below\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1 point\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Lignification\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Immune to mind-affecting spells\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Non-\nALIGNMENT: Neutral\nSIZE: S (2'-3' across)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE:\n1 HD = II/45 + 1/hp\n2 HD = II/65 + 2/hp\n3 HD = III/90 + 3/hp\n4 HD = III/125 + 4/hp\n5 HD = IV/165 + 5/hp\n6 HD = V/275 + 6/hp\n\nBarkburrs are animated plant-creatures that arise spontaneously within woods and forests to defend them. They resemble woody limpets with a hard outer carapace and softer interior. Their lairs always consist of one or more oddly shaped trees, which are in fact the transformed remains of earlier victims.\n\nAttached to tree trunks, barkburrs are extremely hard to distinguish from ordinary burrs. Only druids and rangers have any real chance of recognizing them, at 4% plus 1% per level. They usually lair along paths where travelers are likely to pass.\n\nBarkburrs can sense acts hostile to the interests of the forest within a 1-mile radius. Anything a druid would find abhorrent qualifies. They attack any humanoid coming within 20 feet if that creature has committed such an act within that radius, or if the creature's alignment includes evil.\n\nA barkburr attacks by springing suddenly from its tree onto a victim up to 20 feet away. Unless recognized, it always surprises. It tries to fasten its soft underside to the victim and insert a barbed tube, inflicting 1 point of damage. This full attack routine is resolved as a single attack by a 6-hit-dice monster.\n\nIf the attack fails, the barkburr falls to the ground, where it is nearly helpless. If it succeeds, it begins injecting a lignifying poison on the next round, continuing for up to 2 rounds plus 1 round per hit die of the barkburr each day. Each round the victim must save vs. poison or begin transforming into a small tree. This process takes 1 turn once begun and will continue even if the barkburr is killed or removed.\n\nMost close-fitting equipment becomes enclosed by bark. Swords, shields, rings, and similar objects may remain exposed or become entangled in roots or branches. Enclosed gear other than magic items, precious metals, and gems is absorbed into the wood in 2-7 hours.\n\nA barkburr may be removed by killing it, by fire, or by forcing it sideways. Attacks against it are made against AC 0; missed blows must then be rolled again against the victim's armor class. Fire applied to the carapace inflicts only 1 point of damage per round and has a cumulative 15% chance per round of dislodging the barkburr, though the victim also suffers fire unless protected. Pulling the creature directly away will not work, but twisting or shoving it sideways will succeed if 5d10 is less than the total applied Strength; success inflicts 1-10 damage on the victim as the barbed tube tears free. Up to three persons may help.\n\nOn the ground a barkburr crawls only ½\", can be flipped over readily, and then presents AC 8 underneath. Fire applied there causes normal damage.\n\nOnce lignification begins, the victim is helpless in tree form for a number of days equal to its levels or hit dice. At the end of that time, roll percentile dice:\n\n01-50 = ordinary healthy tree\n51-70 = adult badger\n71-80 = adult giant weasel\n81-90 = treant (7 hit dice)\n91-00 = druid (1st level; S, I, D, Co as before; W 14, Ch 16)\n\nAdd 10 if the original alignment included neutrality; add 20 if the victim was true neutral. Any result other than druid leaves the transformed creature with no desire to leave the wood.\n\nOnly a full wish restores a creature once the process is complete. During transformation, wish, limited wish, polymorph other, turn wood, or reversed plant growth may restore the victim. Neutralize poison has a 30% chance of success plus 5% per caster level. If cast within 1 turn, any of those spells also halts the initial lignification. Cure disease, remove curse, and dispel magic do not help. A restored victim loses 1 level or hit die for each full day spent in tree form.\n\nBarkburrs reproduce by budding after absorbing the energy levels of their victims. A 6-hit-dice barkburr has a 50% chance to bear 1 or 2 offspring of 2 hit dice each.",
      "source": "Monster Manual II",
      "monsterHD_bonus": "-6"
    },
