      "npc_notes": "DIAKK\n\nFREQUENCY: Common\nNO. APPEARING: 2-16\nARMOR CLASS: 0 or 3\nMOVE: 21\" or 12\"\nHIT DICE: 6+6 or 8+8\n% IN LAIR: 25%\nTREASURE TYPE: Nil\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1 or 2\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-12 or 2-8/2-8\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: See below\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: 30%\nINTELLIGENCE: Low to average\nALIGNMENT: Neutral evil (lawful)\nSIZE: L or M\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: VII/1300 + 12/hp\n\nThe Glooms of Hades are populated by many monsters, the most common of which are the diakka. Unlike hordlings, the next most frequently encountered inhabitants of these planes, diakka are more organized and dislike erratic behavior.\n\nThe usual attack made by diakka when confronted by obviously strong opponents is to attempt to force them into a compact group. The diakka surround the opponents and use audible glamer to make it sound as if more diakka were coming. The largest diakka bound in and out of melee using jump and weakness as appropriate. If at least 4 of these creatures succeed in circling the opponents while giving out their odd hooting calls and croaks for 4 consecutive rounds, the sounds and rhythm of this circling dance evoke a hypnotic enfeeblement with an area identical to ray of enfeeblement. Each subject, regardless of magic resistance, must save vs. spell or become enfeebled as if by a 13th-level magic-user, losing 40% Strength for 13 rounds. Once opponents are thus affected, individual diakka use physical attacks and remaining spell-like powers to kill the prey, and then the whole flock feasts.\n\nAlthough these creatures are not too bright, diakka will not attack stupidly. Upon initial contact, the flock's strongest members will assess those encountered for intent and weakness. Weakness puts an opponent in far more peril than hostile intent. Very powerful hostile creatures will be attacked only if appeasement will not work. No diakk desires to be slain, regardless of whether it is eaten or not, as often happens at the hands of hordlings and other planar creatures. Even other flocks are distrusted because of the strong rule. Occasionally a diakk will be found on the Prime Material Plane, always due to summoning. Nighthags frequently use diakka as guards. Diakka speak the hateful tongue common to Hades as well as their own language.\n\nThere are two sorts of diakka, the tall, 6+6 hit dice, and the broad, 8+8 hit dice. The differences are noted below, but they are not separate races, and any group will have an equal or nearly equal mixture of both sorts. In their lair there will always be 13-16 of these creatures.\n\nWhile a tall diakk can deliver a vicious stabbing attack with its long sharp bill, and the broad diakk tears with its clawed arms, both sorts can also employ the following spell-like powers, one at a time, one per round, at will: weakness by touch in attack, once per day, jump, twice per day, audible glamer, once per day, and enfeeblement by group only as described above.\n\nTall diakka resemble huge storks with bills, human-like heads and faces, and thin human-like arms. Broad diakka resemble huge squat pelicans with foreshortened bills on human-like heads. Instead of wings, these creatures have short thick arms with huge curving claws. Feather color is in sickening hues and combinations and varies wildly. Heads are feathered, but faces are brightly colored and featherless. Legs, bills, feet, claws, and the like are usually black, dark brown, maroon, or deep green. Tall diakka are very fast and give loon-like cries. Broad diakka are rather slow. They make gobbling croaks and caws while attacking.",
      "source": "Monster Manual II",
      "monsterHD_bonus": ""
    },
