      "npc_notes": "FROGHEMOTH\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 2 (tentacles)/4 (body)/6 (tongue)\nMOVE: 2\"//8\" (4\" in normal swamp)\nHIT DICE: 16 (see below)\n% IN LAIR: 40%\nTREASURE TYPE: See below\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1 or 4\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 5d10 or 5-8 (+4)\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: See below\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: See below\nINTELLIGENCE: Animal\nALIGNMENT: Neutral\nSIZE: L (18' long, 10' wide)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: IX/8100 + 20/hp\n\nHuge and weird, froghemoths are found only where there are large swamps or relatively shallow bodies of fresh water, 100 feet or less, containing large life forms that serve as prey. Froghemoths are solitary except during spring mating season. In late spring, females lay only 10-100 eggs about 1 foot in diameter. These are left in shallow water. When the tadhemoths hatch, about 90% are eaten by earlier-hatching fellows or other predators. The few survivors search for deeper waters to grow in for 3 years to adulthood. Survival rate is only about 1-4%.\n\nThe tentacles of a froghemoth are very strong and covered with thick, leathery hide. Each of the 4 is about 15 feet or more in length. The body is only slightly less well protected than the tentacles. Each tentacle requires 19-22 hit points to sever or disable, while the body can withstand a full 16 hit dice of damage, 16-128 points, before the creature is slain. Injured members heal or regenerate in 2-5 weeks. The tongue is the most vulnerable attack appendage, taking only 12-16 hit points to sever.\n\nMovement in water is fairly rapid, the webbed rear feet kicking to thrust the monster forward. In marsh or swamp, a froghemoth moves by lying on its belly and sliding along, propelled by rear legs and tentacles. On dry land, movement is by short vaulting hops, the tentacles thrust well ahead and the legs lifting the body forward and up.\n\nThe only treasure a froghemoth might have is that dropped by victims. Most prey is slain and devoured away from the lair, which is usually a submerged collection of trees and debris. Normal hunting is from ambush. The monster will float with its body submerged, retractable eye-stalk raised to just break the water, nostril stalks likewise, and the 4 tentacles thrust ahead, possibly near shore, to seize unwary victims. Another ambush mode is to crouch amid shielding vegetation and lash out with its 10-foot long barbed tongue, Strength 18/50, when prey comes within range. The tongue retracts instantly, dragging the victim to the toothy maw to be swallowed whole on a 19 or 20, 14-20 if size S. Otherwise damage is 5-50 hit points from biting and chewing.\n\nCreatures swallowed whole suffer an immediate 4-16 points of damage from digestive juices. They can attack the stomach only with dagger or similar short stabbing weapons, excluding short swords. Each successive round inside inflicts another 4-16 points of damage. The victim is unconscious after 2 rounds. When hit points equal -10 or less, the victim is digested and totally gone, making resurrection impossible.\n\nIf a victim seized by tongue attack is not surprised, the 1d6 result, 3-6, is compared to a 1d8 result rolled for the speed and accuracy of the froghemoth. If the victim's score equals or exceeds the froghemoth's, it can attempt to grab a stationary object and resist being drawn to the mouth. If such an object is within reach, and the grab succeeds, the hold remains unless the prey's Strength exceeds 18/50, in which case comparison continues each round after being seized. A lower result than the froghemoth's 1d8 means the hold is broken and the victim is bitten or swallowed instantly. The tongue-held creature cannot attack the tongue, but associates can. Meanwhile the monster will use its tentacles to damage the resisting prey and any helpers. If the tongue is severed, the froghemoth will attack for 2-5 rounds with its tentacles, each doing double damage, 10-16 hit points. If still opposed thereafter, it will retreat to submerge and heal.\n\nNormal fire will not harm a froghemoth, but very large or very hot fires cause half normal damage and drive it back for 1 round. Burning hands will not do so unless 10 or more points of damage are inflicted. Fireball, flame strike, and similar attacks will. Electrical attacks do only 1 point per die of damage and slow the creature to half movement and attacks for 1 round. Other forms of attack do normal damage.\n\nA froghemoth has a yellow underbelly; the undersides of the rear legs and tentacles are pale yellowish. Sides are light green and back and upper legs and tentacles are mottled green. The ocular appendage is yellow-green, as are the 2 nostril stalks. Eyeballs are amber with a greenish tinge and the slit vertical pupils are bright green edged with orange.\n\nTADHEMOTH STAGE\n\nThe immature froghemoth grows about 1 foot per month for 6 months, then slows by 60% until maturity. The early form has 4 fins in the pectoral area and 2 in the rear. The creature is fish-like and has a vicious bite for 2-8 points of damage. After 6 months the pectoral growths begin lengthening into tentacles, while the rear members remain largely unchanged until the last month or two, when they lengthen into thick bowed legs with webbed toes. After initial growth, the mouth enlarges considerably and damage becomes 3-24, 4-32, or 5-40 depending on size. A tadhemoth is wholly aquatic and has gills. It swims at 16\".",
      "source": "Monster Manual II",
      "monsterHD_bonus": ""
    },
