      "monstermorale": "",
      "npc_notes": "GREATER BASILISK\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-2\nARMOR CLASS: 2\nMOVE: 6\"\nHIT DICE: 10\n% IN LAIR: 50%\nTREASURE TYPE: H\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-6/1-6/2-16\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Gaze, poison claws, poisonous breath\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Surprised only 1 in 6\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Low\nALIGNMENT: Neutral (evil)\nSIZE: L (12' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: VII/3000 + 14/hp\n\nThe greater basilisk is a larger cousin of the common basilisk. Both are eight-legged, slow-moving reptilian horrors, but the greater form is more dangerous and is often employed as a guardian beast.\n\nIt attacks by rearing up and raking with its claws while biting with a powerful maw. Its claws carry a weak poison; saving throws against this are made at +4. Its breath is more lethal. Any creature within 5 feet of its mouth must save vs. poison at +2 each round of exposure or die.\n\nWorst of all is its gaze, which turns victims to stone. Even when a polished reflector is used in good light, the greater basilisk has only a 10% chance to catch its own reflected gaze and petrify itself unless the mirror is within 10 feet. Its gaze reaches 50 feet, but the creature is nearsighted and cannot see its own reflected gaze unless the reflector is close.\n\nLike the ordinary basilisk, the greater form sees into the Astral and Ethereal planes. It is said to originate on the Elemental Plane of Earth. Its coloration resembles that of lesser basilisks.",
