      "monstermorale": "",
      "npc_notes": "HAUNT\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 0/victim's AC\nMOVE: 6\"/as possessed victim\nHIT DICE: 5/victim's hp\n% IN LAIR: Nil\nTREASURE TYPE: Nil\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1/1, as 5 HD monster\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: See below/by weapon\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Possession\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below/none\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Non-\nALIGNMENT: Any\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: IV/165 + 5/hp\n\nA haunt is the restless spirit of a person who died leaving a vital task unfinished. A haunt inhabits an area within 6\" of the site where it died. Its sole purpose is to possess a living body and use it to complete the task, thus gaining final release. Haunts can assume either of 2 forms at will: a hovering luminescent ball of light, identical in appearance to a will-o-wisp, or a nebulous translucent image of the haunt's former body. Haunts are similar in appearance to a groaning spirit, spectre, or ghost, and are often mistaken for such beings.\n\nA haunt's attack drains 2 points of Dexterity per hit. As Dexterity is drained, the victim suffers the penalties of lower Dexterity. The victim feels an increasing numbness and cold creeping over the body. When Dexterity reaches zero, the haunt steps into the body and possesses it. Once a body is possessed the Dexterity returns to normal. The haunt then uses the body to complete its unfulfilled task, which need not necessarily be dangerous. Once the task is completed, the haunt passes to final rest and the victim regains control of the body. When the haunt leaves, the victim's Dexterity becomes 3. Lost Dexterity is regained at the rate of 1 point for each turn of complete rest. If a haunt's possessed body is slain, it will haunt the place where that body was killed.\n\nIf the possessed victim has an alignment opposite that of the haunt, good versus evil, the haunt will try to strangle the character. It fastens its ghostly hands around the neck on a successful hit. The victim then takes 1 point of damage the first round, 2 the second, 4 the third, and so on, doubling each round until dead or until the haunt is driven off. Haunts may not be turned because they are linked to the site of their deaths. In their natural forms, haunts can be struck only by silver and magical weapons and by fire. Weapons cause only 1 point of damage per attack plus magical bonuses. Fire inflicts 1 point of damage per round, and magical fire does full damage. When reduced to zero hit points, a haunt fades away but reforms in 1 week unless exorcised. Exorcism destroys a haunt forever. Any attacks on a possessed character do full damage to that character. The only safe ways to free a possessed person are exorcism or hold person. If hold person is used, the haunt must save vs. paralyzation or be expelled. A haunt must remain within 6\" of the place where it died until it possesses a body. The best defense is to leave the area it inhabits.",
