      "morale": "",
      "monstermorale": "",
      "npc_notes": "NEREID\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: 10\nMOVE: 12\"\nHIT DICE: 4\n% IN LAIR: 100%\nTREASURE TYPE: X\nNO. OF ATTACKS: Nil\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: Nil\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Spit; controls water in lair\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Kiss; mesmerize men\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: 50%\nINTELLIGENCE: Very\nALIGNMENT: Chaotic\nSIZE: M\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: IV/200 + 4/hp\n\nNereids are creatures from the Elemental Plane of Water. Their name means \"the honeyed ones,\" and they can assume human form when not in the water. These forms are always beautiful and mostly female. Nereids are depicted as young and slim, with long golden hair and pale white skin, and they possess beautiful voices. They may be garbed in white and gold, though they are often unclothed. They have a white shawl which they carry or wear draped over head and shoulders. In water a nereid is transparent and 95% undetectable except as golden angel seaweed.\n\nThese creatures may be found in the sea, rivers, wells, mountain and cavern springs, and on the Elemental Plane of Water. Like the water they inhabit, their motives are chaotic and capricious, though whether they are good, neutral, or evil depends on the individual. The majority are chaotic neutral, but some are very good and others diabolically evil. All nereids are shy and flighty, and their antics have a playful quality.\n\nThe nereid's only physical attack is her spittle, range 20 feet, which may blind a target for 2-12 rounds if it hits. This venom may be washed away with water. A blinded victim attacks at -4 and has saves and armor class worsened by 4. A nereid has some control over the water in which she lairs within a radius of 3\". She can make the water heave in great waves, slowing movement to one-fourth normal, or boil and froth, increasing the chance of drowning by 10%. She can cause crashing waves loud enough to deafen characters within 6\" for 3-12 rounds if precautions are not taken. Finally, she may form watery shapes for amusement or defense, usually a watery serpent or fist which strikes as a 4-hit-dice monster and inflicts 1-4 points of damage. Only one such attack may be made per round.\n\nAll males who look at a nereid find themselves incapable of causing her harm, and her actions seem casual flirtations. Men have been known to sit and watch her antics all day. Many have sought to take a nereid for a wife or pursue her for her embrace. This may prove disastrous, for while the kiss of a nereid can bring sweet bliss, it may also bring watery doom. If a nereid is caught, she may save vs. poison and, if successful, flow away like water. Still, if a kiss is forced from a nereid, the player character must save vs. breath weapons at -2 or drown instantly; otherwise the result is ecstasy.\n\nThe nereid's greatest weakness lies in her shawl, for it contains her soul. If the shawl is destroyed, the nereid dissolves into formless water. Thus, if a character can obtain the shawl, the nereid can be commanded out of fear. However, she will lie and attempt almost anything short of open hostility to regain it.\n\nNereids are 85% likely to have a pet. Roll 1d8: 1 giant eel, 2 giant otter, 3 giant poisonous snake, 4 giant octopus, 5 giant squid, 6 dolphin, 7 giant leech, 8 sting ray.",
