      "monstermorale": "",
      "npc_notes": "QUICKWOOD (SPY TREE)\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1 (90%), 2-4 (10%)\nARMOR CLASS: 5\nMOVE: 1\" (3\" for roots)\nHIT DICE: 5-10 (5 hp/die)\n% IN LAIR: 100\nTREASURE TYPE: See below\nNO. OF ATTACKS: Special\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: Special\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: See below\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Never surprised\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: See below\nINTELLIGENCE: Very\nALIGNMENT: Neutral\nSIZE: L\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: V/350 + 10/hp\n\nIt is said that the quickwood grows only through the magical offices of some great wizard, or possibly druid, who planted a mandragora root after ensorcelling it with mighty spells. Others claim that these weird trees are a natural progression of vegetable life toward a state equivalent to man's. In any case, the quickwood is certainly sentient, unlike most of the vegetation found in the world. This great hardwood tree appears to be an oak, although close inspection reveals that it has a visage and sensory organs resembling a distorted human face. It is 90% unlikely that the \"face\" will be noticed unless the observer is within 30 feet of the quickwood, or 10 feet if the thing is attempting concealment by not using its sensory organs. These creatures may be found in any habitat supporting normal oak trees, including warmer regions where live oaks are found.\n\nAs it is very difficult for a quickwood to move its massive trunk, the creature normally remains still if at all possible. It can, however, send out thick roots moving at 3\" per round through the loose topsoil. These roots can seize and hold immobile any creature under 1,000 pounds. The roots are too strong to be broken, and blunt weapons do not damage them, but an edged weapon may be used to sever one. Treat roots as large, with 10 hit points each. Damage to roots does not accumulate toward destruction of the quickwood proper.\n\nThe creature allows only 6 of its roots to be severed before withdrawing the remaining 7-12 to safety. It also possesses numbers of lesser roots used to sense approaching creatures. Its sensitive leaves can detect air movements and changes in pressure.\n\nThe visual, auditory, and olfactory organs are slightly superior to human norm, and the creature can see infravisually to 120 feet. In addition, a mature spy tree can cause 2-8 normal oaks to serve as its hosts. These trees resemble the quickwood while so possessed, having visages and sensory organs through which the master tree controls the hosts and gains information. Such control extends up to 36\".\n\nThe limbs of the creature are too stiff to serve offensively, but a quickwood has a mouth-like opening that can clamp shut for 3-12 points of damage. The victim must be touching the trunk or forced into such a position by a nearby grasping root before this becomes an actual danger. The roots themselves do no damage and have a range of 30 yards.\n\nIt is possible to use plant-effective spells against a quickwood, but most others do not work. The creature can perspire, drenching itself in water so that fire does not harm it. Lightning is harmlessly channeled off. Poisons and gases do not harm a quickwood. Disintegrate certainly destroys one. However, if under spell attack, a quickwood channels the spell energy into fear in a radius equal to 10 feet per spell level. If the spellcaster fails a saving throw, all spell energy is converted into fear; otherwise fear is only a side effect and the magic has its standard effects. Mind-affecting spells do not affect a quickwood.\n\nQuickwoods are sometimes charmed or otherwise convinced to serve as repositories for treasure or as guardians of an area. In the former role, the guarded treasure is typical of the creature that placed it there, and such items are always stored within the trunk orifice of the quickwood. As a guardian, the creature spies for intruders and, upon sighting them, sends out a hollow drumming sound audible for a mile or more.",
      "source": "Monster Manual II",
      "monsterHD_bonus": ""
    },
