      "npc_notes": "SHADE\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare (rare)\nNO. APPEARING: Typically 1-2\nARMOR CLASS: As original creature\nMOVE: As original creature\nHIT DICE: As original class and level\n% IN LAIR: Variable\nTREASURE TYPE: Variable\nNO. OF ATTACKS: As original class and level\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: By weapon type\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: See below\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Variable (see below)\nINTELLIGENCE: Low to genius\nALIGNMENT: Any (except good)\nSIZE: As original creature\nPSIONIC ABILITY: As original creature\nAttack/Defense Modes: As original creature\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: Variable\n\nAll knowledgeable authorities agree that shades are, or were, normal humans who through arcane magic or dark sciences have traded their souls or spirits for the essence of shadowstuff. While still retaining the shape and abilities of their original species, they have grown in power by joining with this shadowstuff. The true native shade is unknown, and no one knows if shades are connected with the shadow or with some power or substance from the Plane of Shadow. The method of transmutation from living being to unliving shade life has been lost.\n\nAny human or demihuman, if the formula is rediscovered, can become a shade. Dwarves, elves, gnomes, half-elves, halflings, humans, and an occasional half-orc are known to have forsaken goodness for the dark lure of shadowstuff. Becoming a shade does not alter species limitations of ability, class, or level except as described below. The stuff of shadow prolongs the life of shades, for unless they meet with an accident or are killed, they are undying. Disease has no effect on them once they enter shadow, and they may regrow body parts lost in combat, save the head, in 1-4 weeks. This unnatural vitality also manifests itself in regeneration of hit points at 1 point per turn.\n\nBecause of changing light on the Prime Material Plane, shades live in the Plane of Shadow whenever possible, where they are rare. They do not leave that plane unless sufficiently motivated, such as by treasure, enforced servitude, revenge, and the like. Shades wield great power in shadows, but as shadows diminish, whether from increase in light or darkness, so too wanes the power of these shadow-beings.\n\nA shade's power varies by light condition as follows: bright light or sunlight gives ability scores -2, standard magic resistance with saves at -4, hit points -2 per die, and no special abilities; average light gives ability scores -1, magic resistance 5% per level, hit points -1 per die, and no special abilities; twilight gives normal ability scores, magic resistance 5% per level, normal hit points, and shadow-walk; shadowy light gives ability scores +2, magic resistance 5% per level, hit points +1 per die, and both shadow-walk and shadow images; night or dark gives ability scores +1, magic resistance 5% per level, normal hit points, and shadow-walk; complete darkness gives normal ability scores, standard magic resistance, normal hit points, and no special abilities. Shades are most vulnerable in cases of total light and total darkness. Magic resistance can never exceed 60%.\n\nLight affects a shade's ability statistics. Bonuses exceed normal species maximums except for Strength. Each +1 adds 10% to 18 Strength, and scores over 18/00 are treated as 19 Strength. Penalties lower Strength by a full point, so 18/00 drops to 17 at -1 and 16 at -2. Hit point adjustments are per die, and no hit die may be reduced below 1 point.\n\nAll shades have the following special spell-like abilities depending on local light. Shadow-walk is the ability to gather shadows around themselves and use them to transport themselves to the Plane of Shadow; this requires 1 full round. Shadow images is the ability to form exact duplicates out of shadow and cause them to act as if they were living entities. A shade can create 2-5 shadow images and can control their actions as long as they remain within 30 feet. These images may be dispelled only by altering local lighting conditions. They have no material substance and do no damage in attacks.\n\nAll shades may hide in shadows in twilight, shadowy light, and night or dark. They hide as a thief of the same level. Shades with thieving ability gain 2% per level in shadowy conditions and 5% per level in night or dark conditions. Shades with psionic ability may have those powers enhanced, but psionic ability cannot be gained by becoming a shade. Such shades lose all mastery in invisibility and etherealness but gain 2 levels in dimension walking while in shadows. They also usually gain shape alteration, 10% chance per year as a shade, if not already possessed. New power and discipline gained by such a shade operate only on the Plane of Shadow.\n\nA shade's appearance differs only subtly from its mortal form. Its eyes show no white, only a dark gray or purple iris and pupil, and its skin tone becomes dusky and gray. Shades prefer garb of gray or black and rarely wear bright colors. The transformation carries evil in it, for the shade becomes gloomy and brooding. They are generally solitary, unable to trust other shades and unable to deal with normal creatures except through domination or exploitation.",
      "source": "Monster Manual II",
      "monsterHD_bonus": ""
    },
