      "npc_notes": "SPECTATOR\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-2\nARMOR CLASS: Body 4, eyes 7\nMOVE: 10\" (MC:B)\nHIT DICE: 4+4\n% IN LAIR: 100%\nTREASURE TYPE: See below\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: See below\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: 5%\nINTELLIGENCE: Very to high\nALIGNMENT: Lawful neutral\nSIZE: L (4' diameter)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Special\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: V/350 + 9/hp\n\nThe spectator is a guardian of places and treasures. Once given a task, it guards for up to 101 years and will let no one use, borrow, or examine the item or treasure. The treasure being guarded is 90% likely to be a magic item or have a value of at least 15,000 gp. If the spectator gains incidental treasure while performing its duty, this does not trouble its conscience and such treasure may be taken freely. Incidental treasure can amount to the following: 40% for 3-300 coins of mixed types; 30% for 1-6 gems of base value 50 gp; 20% for 1-4 potions; 15% for a +1 piece of armor; 15% for a +1 weapon; and 5% for a miscellaneous magic item valued under 10,000 gp.\n\nSpectators are summoned from Nirvana by monster summoning V and the sacrifice of 3 small eyes, or more, from a beholder. The spectator can be commanded only to guard some treasure. It performs no other duty, and if commanded otherwise it returns to Nirvana immediately. If its guarded item is destroyed or successfully stolen, the spectator is released from service and may return to Nirvana. The summoner may, of course, take the item himself and thereby release the spectator.\n\nThe spectator has a large central eye and 4 smaller eyestalks protruding from the top of its spherical body. The body surface is covered in tough hide and thus is AC 4. Any general blow is 70% likely to hit the body, which contains all the beast's hit points. Hits on the eyestalks or central eye, AC 7, occur 30% of the time, 20% for eyestalks and 10% for the central eye. Any such hit destroys the eye. A spectator blinded in every eye cannot defend its treasure and teleports to Nirvana. This is the only condition under which it leaves its post. Its eyes regenerate in 1 day, after which it returns, unless the treasure is gone, in which case it returns to Nirvana.\n\nThe beast has a general magic resistance of 5%. However, when the central eye is undamaged it can reflect 1 spell fired at it per round and turn the spell back to the caster. This does not apply to touch spells. Reflection occurs only if the spectator makes a saving throw vs. spells. If that fails, it then rolls for normal magic resistance. Reflection is possible only if the spell caster stands before the central eye within a 60-degree arc. Range is not a factor. The central eye can reflect only 1 spell per round even if 2 arrive in the same segment.\n\nThe other eyes have the following powers. Eye 1: create food and water. Eye 2: cause serious wounds at 60 feet against 1 target for 2d8+3 damage, save vs. spells for half. Eye 3: paralyzation ray, 90 feet, 1 target, duration 5-20 rounds. Eye 4: telepathy, 120 feet, 1 target only, with the ability to implant a suggestion to leave in peace if the target fails a saving throw. Initiative for the spectator is rolled on 1d8 instead of 1d6. All 3 attack eyes can be brought into play. Wounding or paralyzation takes 1 segment, as does suggestion; communication takes 2 segments; creating enough food and water for a large meal takes 1 full round.\n\nThe spectator can sense psionic disciplines, powers, and spell-like effects at a range of 240 feet, even through wood, though not through metal or stone. Thus it is difficult to surprise, only on a 1 on 1d12. Being basically passive, it attempts to communicate and implant its suggestion as its first act unless immediately attacked. In close combat the spectator can bite for 2-5 points of damage. If properly confronted, the spectator can be quite friendly. It tells a party exactly what it guards early in the conversation so there will be no argument. If its charge is not threatened it can be amiable and talkative via telepathy. Spectators move by very rapid levitation in any direction and drift aimlessly when asleep, 20% likely when encountered, never touching the ground.",
      "source": "Monster Manual II",
      "monsterHD_bonus": "4"
    },
