  "monster_manual_ii_stegocentipede": {
    "name": "STEGOCENTIPEDE",
    "source": "Monster Manual II",
    "sheet": {
      "frequency": "Very rare",
      "no_appearing": "1",
      "armorclass": "3/6",
      "movement": "15\"",
      "monsterHD": "9",
      "percent_in_lair": "Nil",
      "treasure_type": "Nil",
      "no_of_attacks": "1 and 1",
      "damage_attack": "2-8 and 3-12",
      "special_attacks": "Poison",
      "special_defenses": "Spine armor",
      "magic_resistance": "Standard",
      "intelligence": "Non-",
      "alignment": "Neutral",
      "size": "L (18' long)",
      "psionic_ability": "Nil",
      "attack_defense_modes": "Nil/nil",
      "level_xp_value": "VII/1700 + 12/hp",
      "monsterhd": "9",
      "monsterhd_bonus": "",
      "morale_base": "",
      "morale": "",
      "monstermorale": "",
      "npc_notes": "STEGOCENTIPEDE\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 3/6\nMOVE: 15\"\nHIT DICE: 9\n% IN LAIR: Nil\nTREASURE TYPE: Nil\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1 and 1\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 2-8 and 3-12\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Poison\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Spine armor\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Non-\nALIGNMENT: Neutral\nSIZE: L (18' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: VII/1700 + 12/hp\n\nIt is probable that stegocentipedes developed on some far-removed parallel world or were the creation of some insane genetic manipulator. In either case, it is fortunate that these monsters are infrequently encountered. Although stegocentipedes are adaptable to both temperate and tropical conditions, they find nearly any habitat suitable. They tend to be sterile.\n\nThe chitinous plates running along the stegocentipede's spine give it AC 3 in most, 75%, combat situations. Its greater weight and legless tail portion make it somewhat slower than others of its kind. The monster hunts continually, rushing prey and seizing it in its huge mandibles. Poison is injected with each bite, and saving throws apply. The rear portion ends in a thinner scorpion-like tail. This appendage is heavily armored at its tip, effectively forming a ball-like club which can lash 6 feet in any direction to strike opponents. Worse still, this weapon also contains poison. Victims struck by the tail must save vs. poison or be slain. If not slain, they take 3-12 points of damage.\n\nThe stegocentipede raises its spine plates defensively and moves rapidly. The spiked plates at the front are such that any opponents attacking the creature's head are themselves subject to what is effectively a horn attack. If the attack is successful, using a normal to-hit roll, it inflicts 1-6 points of damage. Up to 3 attackers can be subject to this defensive attack because of the creature's rapid defensive motions. Stegocentipedes are about 2 feet high, with back spines adding another 1 to 2 feet when erect. The chitinous plates are in double rows which flatten along the back when the creature is not engaged in combat. Color ranges from light brown to gray-brown, though green specimens have been reported. Each segment of the body has a pair of legs except the elongated tail segment.",
