      "npc_notes": "WOLF-IN-SHEEP'S-CLOTHING\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 3 (root tentacles)/5 (body stump)/7 (eyestalks)\nMOVE: 1\"\nHIT DICE: 9 (see below)\n% IN LAIR: Nil\nTREASURE TYPE: Nil\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1-3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-4\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: See below\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Low\nALIGNMENT: Neutral\nSIZE: S (effective)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil/nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: VI/900 + 14/hp\n\nThis weird vegetable monster lurks in undergrowth or grassy meadowlands. It creeps slowly from place to place, using its 7 root tentacles for locomotion, early feeding, and even to capture live prey. Its 2 or 3 eyestalks are long enough to give the monster excellent wide-angle vision.\n\nWhile the actual body, or stump, of the wolf-in-sheep's-clothing can take 9 hit dice of damage, its appendages can be broken or severed without permanent harm, as it regenerates them in 1-4 weeks. Root tentacles take 19-22 hit points each and eyestalks take 13-16 hit points.\n\nThe creature attacks by luring prey within 12 feet and then striking and grasping with 1-3 of its gnarled root tentacles. A successful strike inflicts 1-4 points of damage and entwines the victim. The prey is then drawn to the stump's maw next round. Damage will be another 1-4 hit points plus a certain bite for 7-12 hit points unless the victim breaks free of the grasping root or roots.\n\nBreaking a root tentacle by sheer Strength requires an unhindered grasp; thus a creature held by a root cannot break it, but may break free. Breaking free requires Strength 13 or greater. Each point allows a 5% chance. At Strength 18, the chance is 30% plus 1% per point of exceptional Strength, so a character with 18/70 Strength has 100% probability of breaking loose. Only creatures with exceptional Strength can break a root tentacle.\n\nThe monster is 90% likely to attack by surprise. It uses its resemblance to a tree stump or its ability to sprout a growth resembling a small furry creature to attract prey. The lure-growth is moved so as to \"look\" at approaching prey and then \"freezes\" so as to be \"unnoticed.\"\n\nThe body appears to be a grayish-brown tree stump 2-3 feet in diameter. Eyestalks are 10-15 feet long, brown near the base, green at the tips, and with pinkish or violet flower-like eyes. Roots are 9-12 feet long. The vertical maw in the trunk has jagged teeth and thick black lips. When shut, it appears to be an old scar on a normal tree stump.",
      "source": "Monster Manual II",
      "monsterHD_bonus": ""
    },
