    "npc_notes": "ASSASSIN BUG\n\nFREQUENCY: Rare\nNO. APPEARING: 2\nARMOR CLASS: 5\nMOVE: 6\"/18\"\nHIT DICE: 1+1\n% IN LAIR: 50%\nTREASURE TYPE: Nil\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-4\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Paralysation\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Animal\nALIGNMENT: Neutral\nSIZE: S (up to 2' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: II/65 + 2 per hit point\n\nResembling giant bluebottle flies with four limbs, miniature arms and legs, assassin bugs are rarely seen except during their mating season, one day in every two months, when a male and female may be encountered flying in search of a host for their offspring. The natural host is human, though demi-humans and, rarely, humanoids may also be used. The male always attacks first, biting for 1-4 hit points of damage while the female stays nearby but out of danger. If the male’s attack succeeds, its saliva paralyses the affected area unless the victim saves at +2. The male continues attacking until destroyed. In aerial combat they are manoeuvrability class C. Once the desired paralysation has been achieved, the female attacks the affected area and, if successful, implants her egg into the victim’s body, then dies. The egg hatches in 13-24 hours, producing 7-12 larvae. During this period only very powerful magic such as limited wish or heal can remove or destroy the egg. Once hatched, each larva causes 1 hit point of damage to the host each hour as it devours internal organs. After two weeks, the larvae burrow out through the original implantation site, causing an additional 5-8 hit points of damage per larva, and then metamorphose into fully grown assassin bugs. While the larvae remain in the host, cure serious wounds kills one larva per caster level above 6th, cure critical wounds kills all larvae, and heal kills all larvae and restores all but 5-8 of the victim’s lost hit points. The eggs are considered great delicacies by trolls, troglodytes, and bugbears. They are 4-5 inches long, oval, and deep blue. Assassin bugs are generally bluebottle-fly blue, with the female a lighter shade than the male; the four limbs are the colour of human flesh, and the wings are nearly transparent with a faint silver hue.",
    "id": "fiend_folio_assassin_bug"
  },
