    "npc_notes": "BERBALANG\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 6\nMOVE: 6\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 1+1\n% IN LAIR: See below\nTREASURE TYPE: D\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-4/1-4/1-6\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Nil\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Very\nALIGNMENT: Chaotic evil\nSIZE: M\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: III/65 + 2 per hit point\n\nThe berbalang is a solitary biped with leathery skin and bat-like wings. Its eyes are white and watery, and its infravision is twice as effective as that of elves, to 120 feet. The creature spends most of each month in an apparently dormant state, hibernating in a well-hidden cave. Though seemingly comatose, it is actually roaming the Astral Plane, where it hunts weaker creatures and engages in bizarre courtship and mating rituals with other berbalangs. If its body is discovered and interfered with during this astral roaming, it attempts to return and reanimate the body, though this may take 1-100 rounds depending on distance. If the body is destroyed, the astral berbalang dies as well, so the creature takes great care to conceal its lair. For three days each month at the full moon, the berbalang returns to its material body only to enter a different trance and send forth a physical projection upon the Prime Material Plane. This projection flies in search of food, specifically a freshly killed human corpse. The projection is physically real in the sense that it can receive and inflict damage, and it duplicates the original in combat, using two claws for 1-4 hit points each and a bite for 1-6 hit points. It may range as far as 3 miles from the body. If the projection is wounded, it immediately flees back to the body at 24\" flying speed, and the body cannot project again for a number of days equal to the hit points lost. If the projection is destroyed, it disappears, and there is a 75% chance the original dies from system shock. If the projection kills a human, it picks up the corpse and flies back to the host body, feeding on it during flight; a fully grown human can be devoured in one turn, leaving only bones, garments, and equipment. If the berbalang survives an attack, it will eventually seek revenge, though this may be delayed while the body recovers. To avoid exhausting its food source or drawing attention, it moves its physical body to a new area every three or four months, always by night and avoiding confrontation while physically present. For aerial combat purposes, both the berbalang and its projection are manoeuvrability class B. How it gains sustenance when only the projection feeds, and how it reproduces when mating occurs only on the Astral Plane, remain unexplained mysteries.",
    "id": "fiend_folio_berbalang"
  },
