    "npc_notes": "CARBUNCLE\n\nFREQUENCY: Rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 2\nMOVE: 3\"\nHIT DICE: 1\n% IN LAIR: 10%\nTREASURE TYPE: Nil (but see below)\nNO. OF ATTACKS: Nil\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: Nil\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Nil\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Low-average\nALIGNMENT: Neutral with chaotic tendencies\nSIZE: S (3' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: I/14 + 1 per hit point\n\nThis small creature resembles an armadillo with an armoured upper surface of small interlocking plates of tough leathery skin. It feeds exclusively on leaves and small insects and is rarely found outside places such as woodland and marshland where there is a good supply of such food. Its upper armour is attractively patterned in shades of brown, while the underbody is light grey flecked with small green patches. Set in its head immediately above its eyes is a large ruby. This is actually part of the animal, and if the beast dies the ruby shatters into worthless dust. A wizard, or someone of similar status, can coax it into surrendering the ruby with charm monster or charm animal. The gem is usually worth 500 gp, with a 25% chance of being worth 1,000 gp and a 5% chance of being worth 5,000 gp. If successfully removed, the gem regrows at the rate of 100 gp value per month, and its value may change each time it regrows. The creature has empathy and telepathy, using the latter to communicate, and it has slight prophetic powers concerning the immediate future. Its empathy lets it understand the character of each person it meets and know what that person knows, though its intelligence only allows it to form very basic concepts. If attacked, it does not resist and is easily captured, but it can will itself to die if placed under duress. It usually approaches a party of adventurers and communicates the value of its gem to them, seeking to accompany the group. Once it gains the party’s confidence, however, its malicious nature emerges, and it will attempt to cause disruption by using selective telepathy and prophecies, true and false, to breed suspicion, hostility, and even violence between party members. More rarely, it may secretly communicate with nearby monsters to provoke them into attacking the party. Sages believe its inability to comprehend death makes it fascinated by combat and mortality, and eager to promote both. Once it has caused enough trouble, it watches events with morbid interest and then quietly slips away.",
