    "npc_notes": "FROST MAN\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 5\nMOVE: 12\"\nHIT DICE: 4\n% IN LAIR: 20%\nTREASURE TYPE: C\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: By weapon type\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Ice blast\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Average\nALIGNMENT: Lawful evil\nSIZE: M\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: III/125 + 4 per hit point\n\nBecause of the deadly talent of these creatures, native tribes are greatly afraid of them and call them “ice demons,” though frost men are in most respects like normal humans and may have the abilities of fighters, clerics, thieves, or even magic-users. They carry weapons appropriate to their class. Frost men also have the power, three times per day, to radiate a freezing cone of ice mist, 35' long and with a 10' base diameter, from one eye. When not in use that eye is usually covered by a patch, while the other eye serves for focusing, so there is no reduction in hit probability due to monocular vision. Any creature caught in the mist cone takes 3-18 hit points of damage, halved if a saving throw versus dragon breath is made. To date these creatures have only been encountered singly, and the nature and location of their lairs remain unknown, though it is thought that there are villages of frost men buried in mountain caves in cold regions. Frost men appear as normal human males, but radiate cold easily perceived from as far as 30', though not strongly enough to inflict damage. They dress in loose animal skins and carry their treasure in leather sacks. Based on limited evidence, about 75% are fighters, 15% thieves, 8% clerics, and only 2% magic-users. Clerics and magic-users appear to have developed spell use only to the second experience level in comparison with humans.",
