    "npc_notes": "GAMBADO\n\nFREQUENCY: Rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-8\nARMOR CLASS: 6\nMOVE: See below\nHIT DICE: 4\n% IN LAIR: 100%\nTREASURE TYPE: P, R\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-8/1-4/1-4\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Nil\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Low\nALIGNMENT: Chaotic neutral\nSIZE: M\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: III/85 + 4 per hit point\n\nThese extraordinary creatures are man-sized, with a powerful human torso and two arms ending in sharp claws. Their head is a skull, usually of an animal but sometimes of primitive man, perched on a thin but strong neck. The lower body is a cylinder of skin and muscle that can be compressed like a spring and released, below which are three long, thin, single-toed feet. Since it lacks legs as such, it moves by a series of springs; vertically it can just reach a 14' ceiling with its head, and horizontally it moves at the equivalent of 12\". A gambado’s normal tactic is to stand upright in a 6' pit, with only its skull at ground level. By shoring up the pit and covering it with rock, wood, rags, and bones, it can conceal the pit entirely so that only the skull appears to lie on the ground. If a living creature comes within 2' of the pit edge, the gambado springs out and attacks, first with bite only for 1-8 hit points of damage, and thereafter with bite and claws, the claws inflicting 1-4 each. If melee goes badly, it flees rather than fights to the death. If it kills a victim, it ignores all booty except coins, gems, and small jewellery, which it stores in the pit or in a concealed cache-hole in the side. Though basically solitary, gambados often dig pits near others of their kind; where bones are common, as many as 8 may be found close together, though they do not seem actually to communicate.",
    "id": "fiend_folio_gambado"
  },
