    "npc_notes": "KELPIE\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1–4\nARMOR CLASS: 3\nMOVE: 9\"//12\"\nHIT DICE: 5\n% IN LAIR: 70%\nTREASURE TYPE: D\nNO. OF ATTACKS: Nil\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: Nil\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: See below\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Low-average\nALIGNMENT: Neutral evil\nSIZE: M\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: IV/165 + 5 per hit point\n\nKelpies are intelligent aquatic plant life which in their natural form resemble piles of wet seaweed. They can shape their bodies into whatever form they choose, most often that of a beautiful human woman in order to lure men into deep water. They have also been known to assume the shape of a horse, though even then the substance still looks like green seaweed and the effect is somewhat grotesque.\n\nTo compensate, a kelpie can cast one powerful charm spell per day. If the victim fails a save versus spells at -2, he perceives the kelpie as the most perfect and desirable woman, or other chosen form, and willingly leaps into the water to join it. The kelpie then wraps around the charmed victim, who attempts to inhale water and drown in ecstasy. If left alone, he drowns and is dragged to the kelpie’s lair to be consumed. Even if the kelpie cannot physically reach the victim, he still tries to swim downward and breathe water. If the charming kelpie is killed, the spell ends immediately. Charmed victims attempting to drown themselves take 2–20 hit points of damage per melee round until they either reach the surface for air or perish. Females are immune to the kelpie’s spell.\n\nKelpies are found not only in oceans and seas but also in swamps, stagnant subterranean grottoes, and almost any deep body of water, even artificial ones. They can leave the water and walk on land for short periods, up to 1–3 hours. Because of their slimy wetness, fire attacks do only half damage to them, or none if a saving throw is made. Kelpies are very cunning and prefer to pick off stragglers, lone watchmen, or tail-end members of groups.",
