    "npc_notes": "KENKU\n\nFREQUENCY: Uncommon\nNO. APPEARING: 2–8\nARMOR CLASS: 5\nMOVE: 6\"/18\"\nHIT DICE: 2–5\n% IN LAIR: 20%\nTREASURE TYPE: F\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3 or 1\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1–4/1–4/1–6 or by weapon type\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Nil\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: 30%\nINTELLIGENCE: Average\nALIGNMENT: Neutral\nSIZE: M\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE:\n2 HD: II/28 + 2 per hit point\n3 HD: III/120 + 3 per hit point\n4 HD: IV/240 + 4 per hit point\n5 HD: V/420 + 5 per hit point\n\nKenku are bipedal humanoid birds with wings, clawed hands and feet, and the head of a hawk with a sharp beak. They are mischievous creatures who habitually use their limited magical powers to annoy and inconvenience humans, though not usually to kill them. Every kenku has 4th-level thief abilities and is also an expert fighter, usually wielding a quarterstaff or samurai sword. If unarmed, it fights with two claws for 1–4 hit points each and a bite for 1–6.\n\nGroup composition depends on size: small groups contain a mix of 2 HD and 3 HD creatures; groups of 6 or 7 contain a 4 HD leader; a group of 8 contains a 5 HD supreme leader. Kenku of 3 HD or more develop magical powers. A 3 HD kenku has one 1st-level magic-user spell, often magic missile, and can shape change once every 30 days, remaining in the assumed form for up to 7 days. A 4 HD kenku has all those powers plus another 1st-level spell, often shocking grasp, and can become invisible at will. A 5 HD kenku has all the powers of a 4 HD kenku plus one 2nd-level magic-user spell, often mirror image or web, and may also call lightning as an innate power.\n\nAll kenku have highly developed disguise abilities and can pass for human with only a 50% chance of detection, though the length of the nose often gives them away. They favor kidnapping as a source of wealth and freely offer treasure which is usually false and crumbles to dust within a day. They also appear helpful to humans, offering nonverbal advice that is usually designed to mislead or lure the gullible into danger. Kenku do not speak, seeming instead to communicate telepathically. For aerial combat they are manoeuvrability class D.",
