    "npc_notes": "KUO-TOA\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 2–24 (40–400)\nARMOR CLASS: 4\nMOVE: 9\"//15\"\nHIT DICE: 2 or more\n% IN LAIR: See below\nTREASURE TYPE: Individuals L, M, N; in lair A, Z\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 1 or 2\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: By weapon type and/or 2–5\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: See below\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: See below\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: See below\nINTELLIGENCE: High and up\nALIGNMENT: Neutral evil (with chaotic tendencies)\nSIZE: M (higher levels L)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nLEVEL/X.P. VALUE: II and up / Variable\n\nThe kuo-toa are an ancient race of evil fish-men once driven from the surface world into sea caves and then into the underworld, where they prospered and adapted to life in darkness. They now hate sunlight and are almost never encountered on the surface. Small groups sometimes journey upward to kidnap humans for sacrifice or slavery, while larger bands are found deep underground in the tunnels and caverns connecting to their communities. If more than 20 are encountered, there is a 50% chance they are within 1–6 miles of their lair.\n\nTheir groups are highly organized, including higher-level fighters, cleric/assassins, captains, lieutenants, whips, monitors, and slaves in precise ratios. A kuo-toa lair houses 40–400 adult males plus higher-level fighters, female and young populations, slaves, clerics, and a ruling priest-king, priest-duke, or priest-prince depending on numbers. These communities also have formal religious structures and special religious areas open to all kuo-toa, though their settlements are also frequented by drow merchants and slavers, whom the kuo-toa both fear and hate.\n\nKuo-toa use a range of weapons including dagger, spear, shield, weighted throwing net, harpoon, and short bow. Their harpoons are barbed throwing weapons attached by cords, capable of snagging man-sized or smaller creatures and stunning them while the kuo-toan hauls the victim in for the kill. Their shields are boiled leather coated with a sticky glue so that there is a 25% chance any frontal attack against a shield-bearing warrior becomes stuck fast. Their skin is tough, scaled, and very slimy, and along with their dexterity this accounts for their high natural AC. Their biting attack does 2–5 hit points, and when armed only with a dagger they can bite as well.\n\nTwo or more kuo-toa clerics or cleric/assassins joining hands can generate a narrow lightning bolt that does 6 points of damage per priest involved, save for half, with a cumulative 10% chance per round per participant of occurring. Their special defenses include a slime secretion that makes grappling, binding, or webbing them succeed only 25% of the time. They also have exceptional wide-angle monocular vision and can detect movement even if a creature is invisible, ethereal, or astrally projected, so only complete motionlessness avoids detection. They see in both infrared and ultraviolet and can feel vibrations within 10 feet, so they are surprised only on a 1 in 6. They are totally immune to poison and unaffected by paralysis. Spells that affect humanoids, such as charm person, hold person, and sleep, do not work on them. Electrical attacks do only half damage, or none if a saving throw is made. Magic missile does only 1 point of damage, and all forms of illusion are useless against them. Bright light, however, is hated, imposing -1 to hit on them, while fire-based attacks do full damage and they save against such attacks at -2.\n\nTheir speech includes the underworld trade language, their own arcane tongue, and communication with fish by empathy. Their clerics may invoke Sea Mother to deter creatures from the Elemental Plane of Water. Physically, they are paunchy fish-headed humanoids with huge swiveling eyes, long partially webbed digits, short limbs, pale grey scales with tan or yellow undertones in males, and a sheen from constant slime.",
    "id": "fiend_folio_kuo_toa"
  },
