  "monster_manual_i_dragon_general_notes": {
    "id": "monster_manual_i_dragon_general_notes",
    "name": "DRAGON, General Notes",
    "source": "Monster Manual I",
    "sheet": {
      "monsterhd": "",
      "monsterhd_bonus": ""
    },
    "npc_notes": "DRAGON, General Notes\n\nNotes: Dragons come in many colors, sizes, shapes, and alignments. Two sorts of dragons, the Chromatic Dragon and the Platinum Dragon, are singular individuals, and there are no others of their type. The ten species of dragons have three general size categories, small, average, and huge, according to the size typical of each. This is determined by rolling 1d8: 1-2 small, 3-7 average, 8 huge. This size determination indicates the number of hit dice a dragon has. Dragons pass through eight ages in their lives: very young, young, sub-adult, young adult, adult, old, very old, and ancient. These age categories determine hit points per die, from 1 hit point per die at very young to 8 hit points per die at ancient. All dragons have infravision to 60', and they possess excellent sight, smell, and hearing. Because of these keen senses, dragons detect hidden or invisible creatures within 1\" per age level. Adult and older dragons radiate an aura of fear. Creatures under 1 hit die, and non-carnivorous or non-warlike creatures, flee in panic for 4-24 turns. Creatures under 3 hit dice must save versus magic or be paralyzed with fear 50% of the time or panic 50% of the time. Creatures of 3 or more hit dice fight at -1 to hit unless they save versus magic. Creatures of 6 or more hit dice automatically ignore the aura. The aura is weaker in adult, old, and very old dragons than in ancient dragons, giving saving throw bonuses of +5, +3, and +1 respectively.\n\nA considerable percentage of dragons can speak one or more human tongues in addition to the language of their own species. A fair number of dragons which can speak are also capable of employing magical spells. The chances for speaking, magic use, and sleeping are given in each species entry. A sleeping dragon is found only in its lair. It always awakens if loud noise is made within 30' to 120', if attacked, or on a roll of 6 on 1d6. If attacked while sleeping, opponents gain +3 to hit until the dragon is awake. Dragons may be attacked either to kill or to subdue, and the choice must be declared before combat. Silver, gold, chromatic, and platinum dragons cannot be subdued. Subdual damage is non-fatal battering damage. At the end of each round, the ratio of accumulated subdual damage to total hit points becomes the percentage chance that the dragon is subdued. If the ratio reaches or exceeds 100%, subdual is automatic. A subdued dragon may be sold, usually for 100 to 800 gold pieces per hit point, and subdued dragons can be ridden. However, dragons will not remain subdued indefinitely unless strongly held, well treated, given treasure, and allowed freedom. Older, more intelligent, and spell-using dragons are especially likely to escape or turn on their captors. Evil dragons will not long serve good masters, and good dragons are more likely to kill or flee from neutral captors than from captors of like alignment.\n\nCertain attack forms are more or less effective against various dragon breath types. Breath weapons cause damage equal to the dragon’s current hit points, half on a successful save, and can be used at most three times per day. Cone-shaped breath weapons are 1/2\" in diameter at their point of origin. If multiple dragons are encountered outside the lair, two will be a mated pair and additional dragons will be sub-adults. In the lair, multiple dragons are a mated pair, usually with eggs or very young if applicable. Mated pairs are always 5th through 8th age categories. If young are attacked, both parents automatically breathe first and then attack with ferocity bonuses. Treasure depends on age: very young dragons usually have none, but older dragons gain increasing chances for partial, normal, or enlarged treasure holdings, up to 200% of listed treasure for ancient dragons. Dragons are vain, greedy, and often cowardly enough to be subdued. Their vanity makes them susceptible to flattery, and most can be manipulated by the promise of treasure. Dragon saving throws improve substantially with age and hit points, reflecting the exceptional magical resistance and toughness of dragonkind.\n\nDRAGON, Black\n\nFREQUENCY: Uncommon\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: 3\nMOVE: 12\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 6-8\n% IN LAIR: 30%\nTREASURE TYPE: H\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-4/1-4/3-18\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon + possible magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Average\nALIGNMENT: Chaotic evil\nSIZE: L (30' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 30%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 10%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 50%\n\nNotes: Black dragons are typically found in miasmal swamps or marshes, although they also inhabit subterranean lairs, for black dragons always seek deep, dark caves. They tend toward the midpoint between law and chaos in their evil. A black dragon attacks with claw/claw/bite or breathes acid in a 1/2\" wide stream extending 6\" in a straight line, beginning at head height and traveling in the direction and angle in which the dragon faces. Black dragons that can speak and use magic employ one 1st-level spell for each stage of maturity, from 1 to 8 spells total. Spells are determined randomly and require only a spoken component, but each spell may be used only once per day. Duplicate spell rolls indicate repeated daily use of the same spell.\n\nDRAGON, Blue\n\nFREQUENCY: Rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: 2\nMOVE: 9\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 8-10\n% IN LAIR: 50%\nTREASURE TYPE: H, S\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-6/1-6/3-24\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon + possible magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Very\nALIGNMENT: Lawful evil\nSIZE: L (42' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 60%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 30%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 30%\n\nNotes: Blue dragons prefer deserts and arid lands, though like others of their kind their lairs are always vast caves or underground caverns. They attack with claw/claw/bite or discharge a bolt of lightning in a straight line 1/2\" wide and 10\" long. Speaking blue dragons that can use spells gain one 1st-level spell at each of the first three age stages, one 2nd-level spell at each of the 4th through 6th stages, and one 3rd-level spell at the 7th and 8th stages. Thus an ancient blue dragon knows three 1st-level, three 2nd-level, and two 3rd-level spells. Duplicate spell rolls indicate multiple daily uses of the same spell.\n\nDRAGON, Brass\n\nFREQUENCY: Uncommon\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: 2\nMOVE: 12\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 6-8\n% IN LAIR: 25%\nTREASURE TYPE: H\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-4/1-4/4-16\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon + possible magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: High\nALIGNMENT: Chaotic good (neutral tendencies)\nSIZE: L (30' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 30%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 30%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 50%\n\nNotes: Brass dragons inhabit sandy desert regions, with cavernous lairs often found there. They are forward, officious, and love conversation. They are rather selfish and tend toward neutrality because of this. A brass dragon attacks with claw/claw/bite or breathes one of two weapons: a cone of sleep gas extending 7\" from the mouth to a diameter of 2\", or a billowing cloud of fear gas 4\" wide, 5\" across, and 2\" deep from the ground upward. Creatures within these gaseous clouds must save versus dragon breath or fall asleep or flee in fear. If the dragon is small, saves are at +2; if huge, saves are at -2. Brass dragons that can speak and cast spells gain one 1st-level spell at each odd-numbered age category and one 2nd-level spell at each even-numbered age category. Spells are determined randomly.\n\nDRAGON, Bronze\n\nFREQUENCY: Rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: 0\nMOVE: 9\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 8-10\n% IN LAIR: 45%\nTREASURE TYPE: H, S, T\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-6/1-6/4-24\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon + possible magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Exceptional\nALIGNMENT: Lawful good\nSIZE: L (42' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 60%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 60%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 25%\n\nNotes: Bronze dragons prefer subterranean lairs near large bodies of water such as lakes or seas. Despite their love of wealth, they are basically beneficent. They often assume animal form in order to observe human affairs. They attack by claw/claw/bite or use one of two breath weapons: a lightning bolt 10\" long and 1/2\" wide, or a repulsion gas cloud 2\" long, 3\" wide, and 3\" high which affects creatures within it as a repulsion spell for 6 melee rounds unless they save versus dragon breath. Magic-using bronze dragons gain a 1st-level spell at the 1st and 2nd growth stages, an additional 2nd-level spell at the 3rd and 4th, a 3rd-level spell at the 5th and 6th, and a 4th-level spell at the 7th and 8th. Thus an ancient bronze dragon knows two each of 1st through 4th-level spells. Spells are selected randomly.\n\nCHROMATIC DRAGON (Tiamat)\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: 0\nMOVE: 6\"/18\"\nHIT DICE: 16 (128 hit points)\n% IN LAIR: 90%\nTREASURE TYPE: 100% H, S, T, U\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 6\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 2-16/3-18/2-20/3-24/3-30/1-6\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapons, poison, and magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Genius\nALIGNMENT: Lawful evil\nSIZE: L (60' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 100%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 100%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 70%\n\nNotes: Tiamat rules the first plane of the Nine Hells, where she spawns all evil dragonkind. She hates all good as fiercely as she loves cruelty and hoards wealth. She is seldom outside her lair, but occasionally comes to earth to place a new dragon or seek more treasure. She can travel astrally or ethereally. Although her great size prevents claw attacks, she can bite with all five heads and sting with her tail at the same time, breathe with one or more heads, or cast spells with one or more heads at once. Her heads are white, black, green, blue, and red. Her breath weapons exactly correspond to those of the matching dragon types and do damage equal to a huge ancient dragon of each type: 56 frost, 64 acid, 72 chlorine gas, 80 lightning, and 88 fire. Each breath may be used once per day. Each head also casts two spells: the white head two 1st-level, the black two 2nd-level, the green two 3rd-level, the blue two 4th-level, and the red two 5th-level spells. Each head can withstand 16 hit points of damage before being disabled until the following day. If her body takes more than 48 hit points of damage, she is dispelled to her own plane, or slain if fought in Hell. In her lair she is always accompanied by five consort-guards, one huge adult male of each evil dragon type. Description: the colors of her heads continue down their necks and forebody as stripes, blending into gray, blue-green, and purple over the back and hindquarters, merging into a muddy dark brown tail. Her underbelly and legs are greenish white fading into the upper body colors.\n\nDRAGON, Copper\n\nFREQUENCY: Uncommon-rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: 1\nMOVE: 9\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 7-9\n% IN LAIR: 35%\nTREASURE TYPE: H, S\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-4/1-4/5-20\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon + possible magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: High\nALIGNMENT: Chaotic good\nSIZE: L (36' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 45%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 40%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 40%\n\nNotes: Copper dragons prefer warm, arid, rocky regions in which to place their caves and caverns. They tend to be rather selfish, and many are somewhat neutral in outlook where gain is concerned. Their normal attack is claw/claw/bite or one of two breath weapons: an acid discharge like that of a black dragon, 7\" long by 1/2\" wide, or a cloud of gas 3\" long, 2\" wide, and 2\" deep which slows creatures within it for 6 melee rounds unless they save versus dragon breath. Slowed creatures move and attack at one-half normal. Magic-using copper dragons gain one 1st-level spell in each of the first three age brackets, one 2nd-level spell in each of the next three, and one 3rd-level spell in each of the last two. Thus an ancient copper dragon knows three 1st-level, three 2nd-level, and two 3rd-level spells.\n\nDRAGON, Gold\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-3\nARMOR CLASS: -2\nMOVE: 12\"/30\"\nHIT DICE: 10-12\n% IN LAIR: 65%\nTREASURE TYPE: H, R, S, T\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-8/1-8/6-36\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon and magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Genius\nALIGNMENT: Lawful good\nSIZE: L (54' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 90%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 100%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 10%\n\nNotes: Gold dragons can dwell in any climate, but their lairs are always in solid stone, whether cave or castle. Though they love precious metals and gems and use jewels and pearls as nourishment, they are lawful, just, and good. They can polymorph into animal or human form and are often encountered in disguise. In combat they use claw/claw/bite or one of two breath weapons: fire in a 9\" cone with a 3\" base, or chlorine gas in a cloud 5\" by 4\" by 3\". They can cast spells of 1st through 6th level. At very young age they have one 1st-level spell; at young age, two 1st-level spells. Thereafter they gain two spells of progressively higher level at each new age bracket through old. At very old and ancient age they also gain 6th-level spells. Thus an ancient gold dragon knows two spells of each level from 1st through 6th, and can polymorph self three times per day. As gold dragons are highly intelligent, their spells are always of the better sort, and at least half keep regular spell books.\n\nDRAGON, Green\n\nFREQUENCY: Rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: 2\nMOVE: 9\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 7-9\n% IN LAIR: 40%\nTREASURE TYPE: H\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-6/1-6/2-20\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon + possible magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Average to very\nALIGNMENT: Lawful evil\nSIZE: L (36' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 45%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 20%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 40%\n\nNotes: Green dragons prefer underground lairs in or near bleak woods or forests. They are very foul-tempered and thoroughly evil. They attack by claw/claw/bite or breathe a cloud of poisonous chlorine gas 5\" long, 4\" wide, and 3\" high. Green dragons able to use magic gain a 1st-level spell for each of their first four ages and a 2nd-level spell for each successive age, to a maximum of four 1st-level and four 2nd-level spells. Spells are determined randomly.\n\nPLATINUM DRAGON (Bahamut)\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1\nARMOR CLASS: -3\nMOVE: 9\"/30\"\nHIT DICE: 21 (168 hit points)\n% IN LAIR: 75%\nTREASURE TYPE: 100% H, I, R, S, T, V\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 2-12/2-12/6-48\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapons + magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Supra genius\nALIGNMENT: Lawful good\nSIZE: L (72' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 100%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 100%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 5%\n\nNotes: Bahamut, the King of Good Dragons, dwells in a great fortified palace behind the east wind. About one-quarter of the time he roams the earth in human or other guise, for he can shape change freely. He can travel astrally or ethereally. In combat he attacks with claw/claw/bite or uses one of three breath weapons: cold in an 8\" cone with a 3\" base, a vapor cloud that causes creatures to assume gaseous form for 12 turns unless they save versus dragon breath, or a sonic vibration that disintegrates up to 150 hit points. Each breath weapon may be used twice per day, and all saves against his breath are at -3. Bahamut can employ any magical spells of 1st through 7th level, two each of magical spells and one each of clerical spells per day, for a maximum of 21 spells. He possesses books containing all known spells of these levels. Seven huge ancient gold dragons of greatest ability and loyalty serve him as guards, companions, and advisers, and he is seldom without them.\n\nDRAGON, Red\n\nFREQUENCY: Rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: -1\nMOVE: 9\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 9-11\n% IN LAIR: 60%\nTREASURE TYPE: H, S, T\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-8/1-8/3-30\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon + possible magic use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Exceptional\nALIGNMENT: Chaotic evil\nSIZE: L (48' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 75%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 40%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 20%\n\nNotes: Red dragons usually dwell in great hills or mountainous regions, always making their lairs in subterranean caves and similar places. They are extremely greedy and avaricious. Of all evil dragons, this type is the worst save Tiamat herself. They attack by claw/claw/bite or breathe a cone of fire 9\" long with a 3\" base diameter. Speaking red dragons are 40% likely to use magic. For each age bracket attained they gain one additional spell. At the first two ages they gain 1st-level spells, at the next two 2nd-level spells, at the fifth and sixth 3rd-level spells, and at the last two 4th-level spells. Thus an ancient red dragon can employ two spells each of 1st through 4th level.\n\nDRAGON, Silver\n\nFREQUENCY: Very rare\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: -1\nMOVE: 9\"/24\"\nHIT DICE: 9-11\n% IN LAIR: 55%\nTREASURE TYPE: H, T\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-6/1-6/5-30\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapons + possible spell use\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Exceptional\nALIGNMENT: Lawful good\nSIZE: L (48' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 75%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 75%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 15%\n\nNotes: Silver dragons select mountain peaks, clouds, and similar locales for their abodes. Like gold dragons, they can polymorph into animal or human form, often appearing as kindly old men or fair maidens. In combat they attack with claw and bite or use either of two breath weapons: a cone of frost 8\" long with a 3\" base, or a cloud of paralyzing gas 5\" long, 4\" wide, and 2\" high. Those within the gas are immediately paralyzed unless they save versus dragon breath. Magic-using silver dragons can employ up to ten spells. At the first two ages they gain two 1st-level and then two 2nd-level spells. At each later age they gain one additional spell: 3rd level at sub-adult and young adult, 4th level at adult and old, and 5th level at very old and ancient. Thus a very young silver dragon with magic use knows two 1st-level spells; a young one knows two 1st-level and two 2nd-level spells; and so on. In addition, 25% of magic-using silver dragons have spell books and may select spells rather than being limited to randomly determined ones.\n\nDRAGON, White\n\nFREQUENCY: Uncommon\nNO. APPEARING: 1-4\nARMOR CLASS: 3\nMOVE: 12\"/30\"\nHIT DICE: 5-7\n% IN LAIR: 20%\nTREASURE TYPE: E, O, S\nNO. OF ATTACKS: 3\nDAMAGE/ATTACK: 1-4/1-4/2-16\nSPECIAL ATTACKS: Breath weapon\nSPECIAL DEFENSES: Nil\nMAGIC RESISTANCE: Standard\nINTELLIGENCE: Average (low)\nALIGNMENT: Chaotic evil\nSIZE: L (24' long)\nPSIONIC ABILITY: Nil\nAttack/Defense Modes: Nil\nCHANCE OF SPEAKING: 20%\nCHANCE OF MAGIC USE: 5%\nCHANCE OF SLEEPING: 60%\n\nNotes: White dragons favor chill or cold regions. They lair in icy caves or deep subterranean places. Though less intelligent than most other dragons, they are as evil and greedy as any. They attack by claw/claw/bite or by a cone of cold 7\" long with a base diameter of 2 1/2\". Rare magic-using white dragons can employ a maximum of four 1st-level spells, gaining one at each even-numbered age bracket: young, young adult, old, and ancient. Spells are selected randomly from the 1st-level list, with duplicates indicating repeated use of the same spell."
  }
};

    
